##It's worth listening to! A recording of a talk with a doctor from Shanghai to Wuhan is very real and touching

Function Introduction, the Central Party newspaper, the economic newspaper. Mainstream, authoritative, credible.

This is a recording of a conversation with Zhu Zhuzhuzhuowen, the medical team leader of the Zhongshan Hospital affiliated to Fudan University, which is supporting Wuhan. He told the story of his and his team from their arrival in Wuhan, their arrival in the hospital to their participation in the treatment process. When talking about Wuhan and the people of Wuhan, his voice choked several times. About the protective material, about the patient admission, about the vaccine, about the psychological pressure, about the humanities concern... he comes together, real moving.

'It's our job as doctors to treat patients and fight the epidemic, ' he said. 'We should come. We have a responsibility. '. The epidemic will certainly pass, but according to the development of the disease will take some time, we have to insist on, we will insist on.

Writer Fang Fang commented in yesterday's Wuhan Diary that the recording was "very rational, very restrained and very objective" . "This is a doctor with a compassionate heart, a doctor with a big heart of love and kindness. ".

Here's what Dr Chu has to say about himself:

Arriving in Wuhan

I am Zhu Lianwen of the Biology Department of Peking University. I am currently working as associate dean of the Zhongshan Hospital affiliated to Fudan University. This time I took the medical team to Wuhan to carry out the epidemic treatment work.

At 8:00 p.m. on the 6th, we were instructed by the National Board of Health to organize a team of 130 people, including 30 doctors and 100 nurses. At that time, our hospital prepared actively, organized 30 doctors, 100 nurses, as well as 6 members of the administrative team. I'm a doctor, and I'm the head of the administration team, and four of the six administrators are doctors. The hospital also prepared some protective materials, personal supplies, random consignment of more than 700 boxes, the total weight is 8.98 tons.

We took the chartered flight of China Eastern Airlines 330 to Wuhan at 4:00 pm on the 7th. When we arrived at Wuhan Tianhe Airport, there was not a single plane, only one of US landed. The lights are on for us at the airport, and the airport shops are off. They said we had to turn off the lights after you left, and it was like, I can't tell you how it feels. To Wuhan we go directly to the hotel, the goods from the Wuhan side, a lot. Along the way, across the Yangtze River Bridge to see Yellow Crane Tower, we did not speak, because there is no car, no one, and it is a rainy night, our feelings are very complicated.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Take over the ward

Our assignment was to go to the east wing of Wuhan University People's Hospital and take over two infectious disease wards with 80 beds. The People's Hospital of Wuhan University, also known as the Hubei Provincial People's Hospital, has converted 800 of its 1,700-plus beds in its east wing into isolation wards, instead of ICU, a special isolation ward for intensive care. They worked very hard, and over the course of a few days, they started with 200, then 400, then 800.

On the second day of our arrival in Wuhan, we went to the hospital, checked the venue and met there. Together with our colleagues from the People's Hospital, we had seven medical teams over there in charge of 800 beds. When you're in a new environment, everything has to start from scratch. When the ward to see, everyone is really a bit scary, because through the door is an infectious zone. Although there are two passageways, one for cleaning and one for contamination, and there are three zones between the cleaning zone, the buffer zone, and the contamination zone, separated by two doors, these are very rudimentary, not sensor doors, push with your hands. The wind will blow away. Under these circumstances, even though we've been practicing medicine for years, it's still stressful.

When we set out, I was asked by my boss, zero infection. Say to take how many people go, take how many people safe and sound back, security control is my top priority. After looking at the venue and looking at some of their stuff, I think there's still a gap. I'm just GONNA say it one more time, how to put on a Hazmat suit, how we can help each other.

At 2:00 p.m. on the 9th, we took over the two wards. After I saw the supplies in the hospital room, I wasn't optimistic. People's Hospital has used donated items, many brands, specifications, models are different, and some I do not think it can replace the infectious ward, but they used. People's Hospital doctors from the Spring Festival before the mid-january has not rested, their doctors and nurses than we are much less than, but also insist on, they are not infectious division. The two wards I took over, one for cardiology, one for neurology, but they did exactly what infectious diseases did, and they worked very hard, and they needed help.

On the 9th, when I went to work, I said to everyone, "see if the things in the People's hospital can be used first. If they can be used, they can be used. If they can not be used, they can be used. ". It's not that we can't trust them, it's just that no hospital, no city can provide these adequate protective supplies in such a big demand and consumption in such a short period of time, this must be understood. However, the current shortage of materials, especially the lack of protective supplies, has been greatly alleviated, because the country's production and procurement volume, donations are also increasing, so from the material point of view, it is definitely getting better and better. But there are some clinical things that we continue to move behind us.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The situation of the ward has just been mentioned. It is transformed from the ordinary ward. Compared with the Shanghai General Hospital for Infectious Diseases, it is still relatively simple, but you must use it. There is nothing to say. I must go. Equipment is not enough, oxygen is not enough, all of the pipeline oxygen is not for 800 beds to be large flow of oxygen and equipped. The cylinder was then used, and the cylinder was simply transported downstairs and pushed in by the nurse, so it was very hard work. Now the oxygen supply is better than before, and the instruments are more and more.

Our task is to bring in the seriously ill patients, Wuhan in the community are seriously ill patients. They have nowhere to go! Therefore, the mobilization of national forces, the major hospitals into the general ward isolation ward, Intensive Care Ward. The orders are to collect and treat all the seriously ill patients who are still in the community, and to transfer all the seriously ill patients who are still in other hospitals to the intensive care units of our hospitals.

Those with mild illness go to another hospital or go to a shelter. Now built so many shelter hospitals, the purpose is to centralized management, can not let these patients scattered in the community. Because everyone is a source of infection, some people do need to be treated in hospitals. I think this measure is very good from the implementation level, these patients are indeed collected.

With the hospital

We arrived at a brand-new environment, with the People's Hospital running-in is also very important. We're not familiar with their case systems, their procedures. People's Hospital arranged the original head nurse in the ward and a doctor to accompany us to do, do some coordination and contact work, run-in a week is very good. And now they're still here.

We used to hold a team leader meeting once a day, but now we have to hold it on Monday and Thursday night because the situation has improved. We all have wechat groups, what is timely communication in the group. At the beginning, we 7 medical teams, we have different temperaments, different habits, different ways of doing things, in the head of a team meeting when the table noisy what have. I think this is all for the work, later more and more harmony, but also understand the people's hospital, they are very difficult, they are very difficult.

From the condition of the ward managed by my medical team, we are on track. Although this is a strange virus, but it is not completely helpless, there are certain rules to follow. Although still have a lot of blank spot or doubtful point is not clear, but in clinical processing, everybody feels more and more had the experience.

About the patient admission

Of the 130 people in my team, 30 doctors come mainly from breathing, critical care, and infectious diseases. In addition, to consider how many organs the disease can have, we brought along doctors from cardiology, nephrology, neurology, gastroenterology, anesthesiology, and emergency medicine. Of the other 100 nurses, 40 are from our ICU, and some are from other wards. The youngest worked for two and a half years, and nine of the 100 nurses were male. We've got a lot of good people out there, and we can trust this team.

The patients we receive are decided by the Wuhan Forward Command. They receive patients from various communities and then make an emergency short-term assessment. Patients with mild illnesses are transferred to the shelter. Those with severe illnesses come to our hospital or go to other large hospitals.

With regard to treatment, there are actually a variety of methods that have been developed according to the National Board of Health's diagnostic and therapeutic protocols, 1st to 6th Editions. If the patient shows improvement, two nucleic acid tests are negative, or clinical symptoms are not, to be discharged. The patient goes home to be picked up by the grid liaison, who checks in there, and then he goes home. Later, some patients discharged with positive or clinical symptoms, now the rules do not go straight home, find a fixed place isolation for two weeks, and then back home, some patients transferred to the shelter hospital to continue treatment.

We have 80 beds, so far we have about 70 beds, 80 beds at the peak. We've had six patients die, some of them old, not many of them new. The doctor makes rounds in the morning and in the evening. He goes in wearing a gown, writes out a doctor's order, and the nurse brings him in. With regard to rescue, this kind of rescue in the terminal stage is not something you can save if you want to. In addition to patients with low partial pressure of oxygen, poor oxygen and poor oxygen, there are other organ problems. It turns out that there is a slight difference in basic diseases. This is indeed the case.

The hospital has given each ward four cell phones, two inside and two outside, ready to be contacted by cell phones, which are also meant to contact the patient's family in a timely manner. Our Ward does not allow family visits, there is no escort, if some operations to sign, through Wechat, through voice, and then screen confirmation. If a patient dies, that's how you tell them. So far, communication between the quarantine and clean zones has been good.

According to the instructions of the superior, the hospital has to make a report every day, how many patients are admitted, how many are seriously ill, how many are critically ill, how many are discharged from the hospital, how many are mechanically ventilated, or how many are intubated. Well, there are pros and cons to intubation, right. We're very careful about intubating. What we're thinking about now is how to move forward, how to prevent critical patients from progressing to critical illness, so that we don't intubate, and we don't use ECMO. ECMO is hot right now, but for new coronary pneumonia patients, using ECMO isn't as magical as dealing with other diseases, and there aren't many of them, with a success rate of more than 10 percent.

The first to sixth editions of the diagnosis and treatment plan all have the Chinese medicine recommendation plan, especially some Chinese herbal medicine prescription. Some of our patients are using it in the ward, some of them are using it from the shelter, so let him use it here.

Humanistic care in medicine

When we admitted patients with severe symptoms, the People's Hospital staff is insufficient, they provide medical care is too late, so care for these patients is certainly not enough. When we went into quarantine, it was hard. They're very sick. They need to be cared for. But how? Patient support. Sometimes, but rarely. Some patients can't move with tubes in their beds, can't eat, can't drink. Even those that can walk, that's three meals. How do you wash your clothes? What about sanitation? It's all a question. So in addition to seeing a doctor, our medical staff helped them with personal cleaning, and also sent them underwear, towels, soap, slippers, and a lot of food. Make phone calls for patients, talk to home, video chat. The old lady was lying in bed, and whoever talked to her, who talked to the old man when he could not walk. So medical humanities care, just like we do it. Now things are much better, gradually let them improve the environment and so on.

We divided the wards, and the critical ones moved to one place, the mild ones let them look after each other and talk. Overall, patients are in and out of a state of balance.

About the pressure on the players

When it comes to the pressure of the players, there's definitely. I'm stressed, too, and my stress is zero infection, which is why I stress safety over and over again, without adequate protection, absolutely no rushing, no rushing, and everyone's fine with that. It's not that we hold back, but that we can be more comfortable doing all kinds of diagnostic and therapeutic activities if we take care of our own. One of the kids was pretty nervous, in his early 20s. Wearing protective clothing, three layers of gloves, goggles, and a mask, people are all inside, plus the foot cover, you can not feel the pulse, any operation must be very careful, so it is really difficult, especially the nurses very hard.

We had three fainting spells the week before, and then they just came out. And one of the female nurses, she threw up in it, in her mask. As he spit it out, he thought: Take off the mask, new coronary pneumonia; vomit accidentally inhaled, aspiration pneumonia, either way is bad. They're all children!

There were a few of us with low-grade fevers, around 102, and then the fever went down, and that was that. If you're not feeling well, stay home. We each have a single room, water, food to the door, do not come out alone, but we are in close contact with them. If there's an infection, we'll have to quarantine the whole team. Now it's back on track. Everybody's on time, back and forth. It's 12 kilometers between our station and the hospital. I want to be back as soon as I get out of the shower, get out of the hospital, and go home. Our shift schedule is very close, the driver is also very hard.

We can make sure there are no problems in our lives. Three meals at the hospital, three meals at the hotel, and a lot of donated food. That's got to be enough. A few days there was less meat and less meat, and it quietly emitted a sound, and the really capable man brought us meat, and now many well-intentioned people, each showing his power.

About different treatment options

What's the outcome of our treatment now? I don't know. The general situation is not known until the end, as far as our treatment experience is concerned, the situation is getting better, and fewer and fewer patients are admitted to hospital. The ICU is expanding, and community admissions should come to an end. A lot of our patients are coming in from the shelter. Now the treatment of patients in the shelter also requires fluids and a CT scan. In order to prevent them from developing a serious illness, patients with mild illness still need treatment. Patients with mild illness are also returned to the community for further observation and follow-up.

Speaking of Chinese medicine just now, it's really hard to say. Because I feel the method of Chinese medicine argument seems to be different from Western medicine, so it is not convenient to make too much judgment. You can use it if the patient wants to use it. As for how it works, let's see what happens.

How's The vaccine? I don't think the vaccine's GonNa come out anytime soon. What is the effect of convalescent plasma therapy after all? It is also a step-by-step, should not be exaggerated too much, because there is not a very strict clinical trial. How to design this clinical trial? At each stage the virus can mutate, and the antibodies it mutates into may be different. So it's hard to say how to evaluate it. You could say there's no cure for the new crown.

In the face of the many questions we have, about infection with unknown viruses, or about multiple organ problems, we can try to treat them in terms of known principles and principles. But I think there's a question mark over whether this treatment can be used in a very good (RCT) randomized controlled clinical trial, or even double-blind, in our treatment. But that doesn't mean that the observational or one-arm experimental treatments are meaningless. We need to keep summarizing, even observational studies, but the strength of the evidence that these generalizations provide is not high. For now there is a certain effect, recommended use, we also use. But how to do clinical research, still need to be considered in depth.

Now Pi is a lot of, if qualified patient quantity is insufficient, the assurance of research result is not enough, to clinical exactly have how big directive value, also be a problem. I think we should give up something? I'm talking about the abandonment of the need for so much Pi in clinical research. The state will do the RCT, and all the patients will be put together. Because there are only so many kinds of drugs used, one person to conduct a study, you have to do a multicenter, another big shot to do a multicenter, absolutely conflicting, conflicting on the patient, conflicting on the management.

There is a lot that isn't clear about the virus itself, and there's a lot that isn't As Good as It Gets in our diagnosis. If the patient is negative, do you rule him negative? For example, do pharynx test is negative, can you believe that he is negative? The sensitivity of the reagent is not 100% . Sampling at the time of operation may not be available, the amount of virus obtained may also be below the detection criteria. Clinically speaking, if the patient's symptoms subside and the CT is negative, he should be considered better. If it's "healed, " put it in quotes. Now some patients after discharge and Yang, whether he was discharged when the negative is a false negative, but clinically no symptoms. So there really is a lot of unknowns.

Steroids. When? How much steroids? Oxygen. How much? Immunity-enhancing drugs, such as thymosin injection, and other diseases to fight infection? These are clinical first-line assessment based on the situation. From the NHS, but you still need a team for every step you take. That's why sending experienced, collaborative teams together isn't something a budding doctor can do.

What's the best medicine right now? No one knows. You can use it if it's recommended, and it works. But viral diseases, including the new coronaviruses, are self-healing and self-healing. Whether it's because of the drug we're using, or because it heals on its own, can be explored further. I'm Western medicine, and from a clinical point of view, I'm a big fan of RCT. For now, the only drug that strictly administers RCT is Ridgisivir, but he's double blind until the end of April.

About the resumption of work

We're up ahead. We've got a lot of support from Zhongshan, and we're getting supplies, N95 masks, Hazmat suits, everything. But Zhongshan Hospital is also facing the problem of resuming work. By the time I left, our hospital was running a general clinic, and all surgeries had been closed except for the emergency room. These two days began to recover, there are experts out-patient clinic and general out-patient clinic, also to admit patients to hospital, to surgery. Especially for cancer patients, Spring Festival to now a month, how to do? You can't keep dragging this out. Now we must restore, Hubei especially Wuhan area, is still in this strict state. The rest of the country should be restored, and I personally think it is prudent to return to a normal state of affairs.

Personally, I think it's important to do an epidemiological survey, but it's even more important to be honest and not hold back. It's not something you can ask a question about. If it turns out to be a lie, do you have any punishment for him?

About the feeling of support

If you want to talk about feelings, I think it's pretty bitter. Not Our medical team, but the people of Wuhan. I have been interviewed by the media, what is the mentality of the process? I said, I no longer want to come to Wuhan as a medical team leader. By the time I got to Wuhan, I should have been a tourist, not a medical team leader. As a doctor, as a hospital leader, it is our duty to treat the patients and fight the epidemic. We should come. We're in a different city, we're in a different hospital, we're doing medical work. There are risks, but there are ways to control them. It's what doctors do. It's what we do.

I would like to say thank you for your concern for us, you have good people, good organizations to give us a large number of donations. We are on the right track. The country has the means to maintain and improve our current supply. It should be said that the medical situation is improving, our supply is improving, our patients are improving.

A lot of people have asked me, including my daughter, when will she be back? I really don't know. Depending on how the epidemic develops. Now we can also schedule, according to their own situation to make adjustments, I hope you can be in the front of such a high-intensity environment, to get a reasonable rest, to get a reasonable relief. It was the most frustrating thing for me as a manager, but luckily I have a very good team and I really appreciate them and the credit should go to them.

I'm sure this outbreak will blow over. I'm sure it'll blow over. And it's already moving in the right direction, but it's GonNa take some time for the disease to develop, and we're GONNA keep it up, and we're GONNA keep it up.
